AGI -&nbsp; Sunday will be fifty years from that referendum. Forty-seven will have passed, instead, from the gunshot to Ponte Garibaldi. The divorce referendum (1974), the assassination of Giorgiana Masi (1977), two events shared by the same date, on 12 May. As every year, then, a delegation of the Radical Party will meet on Sunday at 11 am at Ponte Garibaldi in Rome to commemorate Giorgiana Masi, "the young militant victim of a tragic murder, and to continue to pursue the truth about this and all other cases - emphasizes a note - of violence of the nation's raison d'éta". In the afternoon instead, at 17, the headquarters of the Radical Party in Via di Torre Argentina 76 - another piece of the country's political and civil history - will host "a commemorative event to celebrate fifty years from the referendum on divorce", with Lucia Bonfreschi and contributions by Annamaria Bernardini De Pace, Primo Mastrantoni, Mirella Parachini, Maurizio Turco and Irene Testa, respectively secretary and treasurer of the Radical Party.
&nbsp;
"The event - it explains a note - will be an opportunity to remember the long way in the struggle for civil rights and to reaffirm the importance of individual freedom and social justice".

